1
00:01:17,643 --> 00:01:19,577
Hey, sheriff.

2
00:02:29,815 --> 00:02:34,013
A Mercury is a real good car.

3
00:02:34,119 --> 00:02:36,417
That was the car
I was driving that day.

4
00:02:40,292 --> 00:02:43,261
I owned a lot of cars.

5
00:02:43,328 --> 00:02:46,923
Yeah, different kinds.

6
00:02:46,999 --> 00:02:50,730
A lot of different kinds of cars.

7
00:02:50,802 --> 00:02:53,600
She was standing, this girl…

8
00:02:54,840 --> 00:02:57,035
on the side of the street
by this chicken stand.

9
00:02:57,109 --> 00:02:59,373
Not the Colonel’s,
a different chicken stand.

10
00:02:59,444 --> 00:03:02,379
I pulled the Mercury up alongside…

11
00:03:02,447 --> 00:03:05,746
and rolled down the window
by electric power.

12
00:03:05,817 --> 00:03:10,254
And she had this leather skirt on…

13
00:03:10,355 --> 00:03:13,552
and she had a lot of hair
on her arms.

14
00:03:13,625 --> 00:03:16,822
I like that. It means a big bush,
which I like.

15
00:03:20,332 --> 00:03:25,463
She says, “Are you dating?”
You know?

16
00:03:25,537 --> 00:03:27,903
I said, “Sure.”
So she gets in…

17
00:03:27,973 --> 00:03:31,670
and we pull off into…

18
00:03:31,743 --> 00:03:35,110
this remote location
comfortable for both of us.

19
00:03:35,214 --> 00:03:38,809
She says, “How much
do you want to spend?”

20
00:03:38,917 --> 00:03:42,375
I said, “Enough to see
your bush. I know it’s big.”

21
00:03:42,487 --> 00:03:44,887
She says, “$25.”

22
00:03:47,693 --> 00:03:52,687
That’s not chicken feed
to a working man.

23
00:03:52,764 --> 00:03:55,995
I produce the $25,
she sticks it in her shoe…

24
00:03:56,068 --> 00:03:58,036
pulls up her skirt…

25
00:03:58,103 --> 00:04:04,008
and there is thin, crooked,
uncircumcised penis.

26
00:04:09,815 --> 00:04:12,648
You can imagine I wanted my $25 back.

27
00:04:17,756 --> 00:04:19,348
Why are you weirded out?

28
00:04:19,424 --> 00:04:22,484
It’s not San Quentin.
It’s a nut house.

29
00:04:22,561 --> 00:04:25,621
Most patients don’t know where
they are. They won’t hurt you.

30
00:04:25,697 --> 00:04:28,757
It doesn’t bother you we’ll be facing
a killer in a few minutes?

31
00:04:28,834 --> 00:04:31,394
You wanted to major in journalism.

32
00:04:36,942 --> 00:04:39,035
They’re from that newspaper deal.

33
00:04:39,111 --> 00:04:41,671
– From the college?
– Yes, sir.

34
00:04:41,747 --> 00:04:44,511
– I’m Jerry Woolridge.
– I’m Marsha Dwiggins.

35
00:04:44,616 --> 00:04:47,414
She’s Theresa Evans.
She’s here to take pictures.

36
00:04:49,054 --> 00:04:50,988
Y’all sit down.

37
00:04:52,457 --> 00:04:56,052
A man named John Leggitt Hunter
had a filling station.

38
00:04:56,128 --> 00:04:57,493
A good filling station business.

39
00:04:57,562 --> 00:05:00,929
He was the type of person
that I’m sure you’ve met too…

40
00:05:00,999 --> 00:05:02,933
who didn’t deserve what he had.

41
00:05:03,001 --> 00:05:07,734
One thing he had was…

42
00:05:07,806 --> 00:05:10,741
this beautiful, young bride,
Sarah.

43
00:05:12,744 --> 00:05:14,644
She was a Georgia peach.

44
00:05:14,746 --> 00:05:20,548
She was more like the picture I had
in my mind than any woman I’d seen.

45
00:05:20,619 --> 00:05:23,918
So I took her away
from John Leggitt Hunter…

46
00:05:23,989 --> 00:05:26,958
who did not deserve her.

47
00:05:27,025 --> 00:05:30,085
Oh, I don’t know if I told you…

48
00:05:30,162 --> 00:05:33,222
but he was a Frenchman
who claimed to be an Englishman.

49
00:05:37,869 --> 00:05:40,167
Took strong nylon cord
to get her away from him.

50
00:05:40,238 --> 00:05:42,968
She was a fighter and a Georgia peach.

51
00:05:47,412 --> 00:05:50,210
There must have been a mix-up.

52
00:05:51,516 --> 00:05:54,781
I talked to your sponsor,
teacher or whoever…

53
00:05:54,853 --> 00:05:58,016
and told him no pictures.

54
00:05:58,123 --> 00:06:02,219
This is for an article
or something, right?

55
00:06:03,528 --> 00:06:07,020
Yeah, it’s for the school newspaper
which has pictures.

56
00:06:07,099 --> 00:06:08,726
It’s a regular paper.

57
00:06:08,800 --> 00:06:11,860
Karl’s real sensitive
about having his picture made.

58
00:06:11,937 --> 00:06:15,304
He wouldn’t be on the bulletin board
for the Easter collage.

59
00:06:18,710 --> 00:06:21,304
Now…

60
00:06:21,380 --> 00:06:24,349
a shovel just makes
too goddamn much racket.

61
00:06:33,625 --> 00:06:35,957
I’ll talk to him, see what he says.

62
00:06:38,964 --> 00:06:41,364
You gotta make something explode
to truly understand it.

63
00:06:41,433 --> 00:06:45,597
You gotta examine all those particles
while they’re still on fire.

64
00:06:47,639 --> 00:06:50,631
Karl, let’s go down
to the old classroom.

65
00:06:50,709 --> 00:06:53,701
Mr. Woolridge has some people
for you to see.

66
00:06:55,680 --> 00:06:57,614
Let’s go.

67
00:07:16,001 --> 00:07:19,528
Remember I told you about
those newspaper people?

68
00:07:19,604 --> 00:07:22,698
They want to ask you questions
about your release.

69
00:07:22,774 --> 00:07:25,675
They think it’ll make a good story.

70
00:07:25,744 --> 00:07:28,679
Will you talk to them?
Get interviewed?

71
00:07:30,782 --> 00:07:32,682
They’re women.

72
00:07:36,021 --> 00:07:41,425
I think it’d be good for you. You’ll see
all kinds of people on the outside.

73
00:07:41,493 --> 00:07:43,427
This’ll help.

74
00:07:50,435 --> 00:07:55,634
Now, he’ll only talk to you
but you can’t ask him anything…

75
00:07:55,707 --> 00:07:57,698
and don’t stare at him.

76
00:07:57,776 --> 00:08:00,301
How can I interview him
if I can’t ask any questions?

77
00:08:00,378 --> 00:08:02,608
Sorry, that’s the best it’s gonna get.

78
00:08:02,714 --> 00:08:04,614
Can I ask you a question?

79
00:08:04,716 --> 00:08:07,708
If he’s so troubled,
why are you letting him out?

80
00:08:07,819 --> 00:08:10,617
What if he does it again?
It happens.

81
00:08:10,689 --> 00:08:13,556
His time’s up.
That’s the rules.

82
00:08:13,625 --> 00:08:16,992
He’s been treated, re-evaluated,
doesn’t show any signs any more.

83
00:08:17,062 --> 00:08:19,792
– Signs?
– Homicidal signs.

84
00:08:19,865 --> 00:08:25,132
Miss, I’m sorry,
but you’ll have to step outside.

85
00:08:25,203 --> 00:08:27,671
– Why?
– Please?

86
00:08:37,682 --> 00:08:41,083
I have to change
the light in here for Karl.

87
00:08:41,186 --> 00:08:43,711
I hope you can still see to write.

88
00:09:25,063 --> 00:09:29,227
I reckon what you want to know
is what I’m doing in here.

89
00:09:29,301 --> 00:09:32,031
I reckon it’s because I killed somebody.

90
00:09:34,639 --> 00:09:38,234
But I reckon you want to know
how come I killed somebody…

91
00:09:38,310 --> 00:09:40,676
so I’ll start at the front
and tell you.

92
00:09:44,149 --> 00:09:49,018
I lived out in back of
my parents’ place most of my life…

93
00:09:49,087 --> 00:09:52,989
in a little old shed
that my daddy’d built for me.

94
00:09:53,058 --> 00:09:57,392
They didn’t want me in the house
with the rest of them…

95
00:09:57,462 --> 00:10:00,989
so I sat around in the shed
looking at the ground.

96
00:10:03,168 --> 00:10:06,069
I didn’t have no floor…

97
00:10:06,137 --> 00:10:10,301
but I had me a hole dug out
to lay down in…

98
00:10:10,375 --> 00:10:12,502
a quilt or two to put down there.

99
00:10:15,814 --> 00:10:17,782
My father…

100
00:10:17,816 --> 00:10:21,013
was a hard-working man
most of his life…

101
00:10:21,086 --> 00:10:24,715
not that I can say the same
for myself.

102
00:10:24,823 --> 00:10:27,155
I mostly just sat around
in the shed…

103
00:10:27,225 --> 00:10:29,318
tinkered around
with a lawn mower or two…

104
00:10:30,528 --> 00:10:34,225
went to school off and on
from time to time.

105
00:10:34,299 --> 00:10:39,498
But the children out there,
they were very cruel to me…

106
00:10:39,571 --> 00:10:44,008
and made quite a bit of sport of me,
made fun of me quite a bit.

107
00:10:44,075 --> 00:10:49,308
So mostly I just sat around
out there in the shed.

108
00:10:53,051 --> 00:10:55,212
My daddy…

109
00:10:55,320 --> 00:10:58,187
worked at the sawmill,
down at the planer mill…

110
00:10:58,256 --> 00:11:01,020
for an old man named Dixon.

111
00:11:01,092 --> 00:11:03,686
Old man Dixon was a very cruel fellow.

112
00:11:03,762 --> 00:11:07,198
Didn’t treat his employees well
or pay them well.

113
00:11:07,265 --> 00:11:10,132
Didn’t pay my daddy too much of a wage.

114
00:11:10,201 --> 00:11:12,761
Just barely enough to get by,
I reckon.

115
00:11:14,039 --> 00:11:16,303
I reckon he got by all right.

116
00:11:19,210 --> 00:11:21,735
They used to come out,
one or the other of them…

117
00:11:23,181 --> 00:11:25,240
usually my mother…

118
00:11:25,350 --> 00:11:27,545
feed me pretty regular.

119
00:11:28,653 --> 00:11:31,816
So I know he made enough
so I could have mustard and biscuits…

120
00:11:31,923 --> 00:11:34,289
three or four times a week.

121
00:11:37,595 --> 00:11:40,120
But old man Dixon…

122
00:11:40,198 --> 00:11:42,132
he had a boy…

123
00:11:43,168 --> 00:11:45,932
name of Jesse Dixon.

124
00:11:46,004 --> 00:11:49,701
Jesse was more cruel
than his daddy was.

125
00:11:49,774 --> 00:11:53,301
He used to make
quite a bit of sport of me…

126
00:11:53,378 --> 00:11:56,006
when I was down there
at the schoolhouse.

127
00:11:58,616 --> 00:12:02,643
Used to take advantage of the girls
in the neighbourhood.

128
00:12:05,790 --> 00:12:08,281
They used to say…

129
00:12:08,393 --> 00:12:11,521
that my mother was a very pretty woman.

130
00:12:11,596 --> 00:12:16,863
They said that quite a bit
when I’d be there at the schoolhouse.

131
00:12:16,935 --> 00:12:21,963
I reckon you want me to get on with it
and tell you what happened.

132
00:12:22,040 --> 00:12:23,974
So I reckon I’ll tell you.

133
00:12:25,410 --> 00:12:28,607
I was setting out in the shed
one evening, not doing much…

134
00:12:28,713 --> 00:12:31,204
just staring at the wall…

135
00:12:31,316 --> 00:12:34,410
and waiting on my mother
to give me my Bible lesson.

136
00:12:37,822 --> 00:12:41,417
I heard a commotion in the house…

137
00:12:41,526 --> 00:12:45,121
so I run up on the screened-in porch
to look inside.

138
00:12:45,196 --> 00:12:49,963
I looked in and seen my mother laying
on the floor without any clothes on.

139
00:12:56,174 --> 00:12:58,608
I seen Jesse Dixon
laying on top of her.

140
00:13:02,147 --> 00:13:04,240
He was having his way with her.

141
00:13:05,850 --> 00:13:07,750
I just seen red.

142
00:13:11,856 --> 00:13:15,690
I picked up a Kaiser blade that was
sitting by the door.

143
00:13:15,760 --> 00:13:19,856
Some folks called it a sling blade.
I called it a Kaiser blade.

144
00:13:19,931 --> 00:13:23,992
It’s got a long, wood handle,
kind of like an axe handle…

145
00:13:24,068 --> 00:13:26,901
with a long blade shaped like a banana.

146
00:13:28,373 --> 00:13:30,705
Sharp on one edge
and dull on the other.

147
00:13:32,010 --> 00:13:36,470
It’s what the highway boys use
to cut down weeds and whatnot. Yeah.

148
00:13:39,417 --> 00:13:41,317
I went in the house…

149
00:13:42,353 --> 00:13:45,220
and I hit Jesse Dixon
upside the head with it…

150
00:13:45,290 --> 00:13:47,224
knocked him off my mother.

151
00:13:48,626 --> 00:13:51,789
I reckon that didn’t satisfy me…

152
00:13:53,698 --> 00:13:56,223
so I hit him again in the neck
with the sharp edge…

153
00:13:56,301 --> 00:13:59,930
and just plumb near cut his head off,
killed him.

154
00:14:02,674 --> 00:14:05,108
My mother jumped up
and started hollering…

155
00:14:05,176 --> 00:14:08,202
“What did you kill Jesse for?”

156
00:14:08,279 --> 00:14:11,009
Well, come to find out…

157
00:14:11,082 --> 00:14:14,108
my mother didn’t mind
what Jesse was doing to her.

158
00:14:15,787 --> 00:14:19,655
That made me madder
than what Jesse’d made me…

159
00:14:19,724 --> 00:14:22,090
so I took the Kaiser blade –

160
00:14:22,160 --> 00:14:25,425
some folks called it a sling blade,
I called it a Kaiser blade –

161
00:14:27,632 --> 00:14:30,567
and I hit my mother
upside the head with it.

162
00:14:33,638 --> 00:14:35,196
Killed her.

163
00:14:39,878 --> 00:14:42,005
Some folks has asked me…

164
00:14:42,113 --> 00:14:46,015
if you had it to do over again,
would you do it the same way?

165
00:14:46,117 --> 00:14:48,017
I reckon I would.

166
00:14:49,754 --> 00:14:51,722
Anyhow, they put me in here…

167
00:14:51,823 --> 00:14:54,815
and here I been
for a great, long while.

168
00:14:57,929 --> 00:14:59,920
I’ve learned to read some.

169
00:15:01,165 --> 00:15:03,258
Took me four years to read the Bible.

170
00:15:04,702 --> 00:15:07,728
I reckon I understand
a great deal of it.

171
00:15:07,805 --> 00:15:10,433
Wasn’t what I expected
in some places.

172
00:15:12,911 --> 00:15:15,641
I’ve slept in a good bed
for a great, long while.

173
00:15:17,782 --> 00:15:20,250
Now they’ve seen fit
to put me out of here.

174
00:15:20,318 --> 00:15:22,912
They say they’re setting me free today.

175
00:15:26,457 --> 00:15:28,982
I reckon that’s all you was
needing to know.

176
00:15:30,929 --> 00:15:34,831
You want more details.
I reckon I can tell them.

177
00:15:34,899 --> 00:15:38,096
I don’t know whether that’s enough
for your newspaper or not.

178
00:15:39,604 --> 00:15:41,663
Will you ever kill again, Karl?

179
00:15:53,418 --> 00:15:56,649
I don’t reckon I got no reason
to kill nobody.

180
00:16:06,831 --> 00:16:09,299
– Where will he go?
– Anywhere he wants.

181
00:16:09,400 --> 00:16:13,131
I think he’s going to Millsburg where
he’s from, about 20 miles from here.

182
00:16:13,204 --> 00:16:17,334
– Will he be supervised?
– As much as anybody, I guess.

183
00:16:17,408 --> 00:16:19,433
Y’all have a nice day, now.

184
00:16:20,678 --> 00:16:23,112
I’ll get Melvin to walk y’all out.

185
00:16:27,685 --> 00:16:30,017
Would you walk these girls out?

186
00:16:32,323 --> 00:16:34,154
Thank you.

187
00:16:46,371 --> 00:16:50,569
I reckon I’ll have to get used to
looking at pretty people.

188
00:16:50,641 --> 00:16:52,575
Guess you will.

189
00:16:53,745 --> 00:16:56,805
Reckon I’ll have to get used to them
looking at me too.

190
00:16:59,217 --> 00:17:01,685
Better go get your things.

191
00:17:01,753 --> 00:17:03,721
Ain’t got nothing but them books.

192
00:17:05,723 --> 00:17:07,657
Better go get them.

193
00:17:08,760 --> 00:17:10,694
All right, then.

194
00:17:22,807 --> 00:17:24,741
All right, then.

195
00:19:50,421 --> 00:19:52,013
Can I help you?

196
00:19:59,764 --> 00:20:02,892
I was kinda wanting
something to eat.

197
00:20:02,967 --> 00:20:05,026
Well, what would you like?

198
00:20:07,104 --> 00:20:09,766
You got any biscuits in there?

199
00:20:09,874 --> 00:20:13,275
No, this is a Frosty Cream.
We don’t serve biscuits.

200
00:20:13,344 --> 00:20:15,278
We got a lot of other stuff.

201
00:20:15,346 --> 00:20:17,906
What you got in there
that’s good to eat?

202
00:20:17,982 --> 00:20:20,576
We got Big Chief Burgers,
Bongo Burgers…

203
00:20:20,651 --> 00:20:24,178
Foot-longs, Corny Dogs,
Frosty Shakes, Creamy Bars.

204
00:20:24,255 --> 00:20:27,281
Did you want me to go through
the whole list?

205
00:20:28,092 --> 00:20:30,526
What do you like?

206
00:20:32,063 --> 00:20:37,433
Well, the French fries are pretty good.

207
00:20:37,501 --> 00:20:41,232
– French fried potatoes?
– Yep, French fries.

208
00:20:44,008 --> 00:20:45,942
How much you want for them?

209
00:20:46,010 --> 00:20:49,446
They’re 60 for medium
and 75 for large.

210
00:20:53,117 --> 00:20:55,745
I reckon I’ll have me
some of the big ones.

211
00:20:55,820 --> 00:20:57,947
All right.
One large French fries?

212
00:21:39,363 --> 00:21:41,354
These darn things are heavy.

213
00:21:41,432 --> 00:21:43,923
Hard to carry too.

214
00:21:44,035 --> 00:21:46,629
– You got wash in there?
– Yeah.

215
00:21:48,439 --> 00:21:51,431
Can’t your mama and daddy tend to it?

216
00:21:51,542 --> 00:21:56,104
I got a mama but she’s at work
at Hoochy’s Dollar Store.

217
00:21:56,180 --> 00:21:59,672
My daddy’s dead.
He got hit by a train.

218
00:22:02,353 --> 00:22:05,117
How far you going
with them sacks full of wash?

219
00:22:05,189 --> 00:22:07,123
Half a mile, I think.

220
00:22:08,859 --> 00:22:11,692
I can help you tote it
if I don’t give out first.

221
00:22:11,762 --> 00:22:14,162
Okay, but you don’t have to.

222
00:22:16,534 --> 00:22:18,468
All right, then.

223
00:22:21,472 --> 00:22:24,532
My name’s Frank Wheatley.
What’s yours?

224
00:22:24,608 --> 00:22:26,872
Karl’s my name.

225
00:22:26,911 --> 00:22:28,970
– What’s your last name?
– Childers.

226
00:22:31,215 --> 00:22:33,376
What are all them books?

227
00:22:33,451 --> 00:22:35,385
Oh, different ones.

228
00:22:35,453 --> 00:22:37,921
One’s the Bible, one’s a book
on Christmas…

229
00:22:37,988 --> 00:22:40,479
one’s on how to be a carpenter.

230
00:22:40,558 --> 00:22:44,892
– Why do you carry them around?
– Ain’t got no place to set them down.

231
00:22:44,962 --> 00:22:47,055
Don’t you live somewhere?

232
00:22:47,131 --> 00:22:50,032
Did live at the state hospital.

233
00:22:50,101 --> 00:22:54,162
– Why?
– I killed some folks a while back.

234
00:22:54,271 --> 00:22:57,502
They said I wasn’t right in the head so
they put me in the nervous hospital…

235
00:22:57,575 --> 00:23:00,009
instead of putting me in jail.

236
00:23:00,077 --> 00:23:02,671
– They let you out?
– Yeah.

237
00:23:02,747 --> 00:23:06,308
– How come?
– They told me I was well.

238
00:23:06,384 --> 00:23:09,410
Had to turn me loose.

239
00:23:09,487 --> 00:23:12,820
– Are you well?
– I reckon I feel all right.

240
00:23:15,693 --> 00:23:17,661
This here’s my house.

241
00:23:20,765 --> 00:23:24,394
You don’t seem like you killed nobody.

242
00:23:24,502 --> 00:23:26,766
We can just
set these bags on the porch.

243
00:23:26,871 --> 00:23:28,736
All right, then.

244
00:23:44,722 --> 00:23:47,247
You like to play football?

245
00:23:47,324 --> 00:23:50,919
I never was no account at it,
never got picked out for it.

246
00:23:52,329 --> 00:23:54,263
Me and the Barnett twins
and some boys…

247
00:23:54,331 --> 00:23:57,425
play at the junior high school field
all the time.

248
00:23:57,535 --> 00:24:00,834
You want to play, come on over
’cause we ain’t no good either.

249
00:24:01,939 --> 00:24:03,873
I’ll see you later.

250
00:24:03,941 --> 00:24:05,875
All right, then.

251
00:25:01,165 --> 00:25:03,190
Hon, you can’t just go in there.

252
00:25:04,602 --> 00:25:06,900
What in the world are you doing here?

253
00:25:06,971 --> 00:25:08,939
I want to come back and stay in here.

254
00:25:10,574 --> 00:25:12,838
You can’t. You’re a free man.

255
00:25:12,910 --> 00:25:15,777
They let you out so you can
do as you please.

256
00:25:15,846 --> 00:25:18,508
I reckon I don’t care
about being a free man.

257
00:25:18,582 --> 00:25:21,073
I don’t know how
to go about it.

258
00:25:21,151 --> 00:25:23,085
You’ll have to learn.

259
00:25:23,153 --> 00:25:25,348
It’ll take some time.

260
00:25:25,456 --> 00:25:28,289
Don’t you have anybody
to help you out?

261
00:25:28,359 --> 00:25:30,486
No, sir.

262
00:25:30,561 --> 00:25:34,053
Your daddy was living there
last time I heard.

263
00:25:34,131 --> 00:25:38,534
I guess he wouldn’t want to
help you out any, would he?

264
00:25:39,970 --> 00:25:41,904
Sorry. I wasn’t thinking.

265
00:25:44,742 --> 00:25:47,040
Don’t you have anybody?

266
00:25:47,111 --> 00:25:52,208
No, sir. Never did know
too much of nobody down there.

267
00:25:52,316 --> 00:25:54,511
Not to be helping me out,
no way.

268
00:25:57,521 --> 00:25:59,421
Karl, the truth is…

269
00:26:00,724 --> 00:26:04,421
I don’t know where they expect you
to go, what they expect you to do.

270
00:26:04,528 --> 00:26:09,192
If I could, I’d let you come back here
and stay if you wanted to.

271
00:26:09,266 --> 00:26:12,133
I’m just doing my job.

272
00:26:12,202 --> 00:26:14,136
You follow me?

273
00:26:17,575 --> 00:26:20,169
Listen, Karl, I know an old boy…

274
00:26:20,244 --> 00:26:23,645
who’s got a fix-it shop deal
in Millsburg.

275
00:26:23,714 --> 00:26:25,705
He used to go to church with me.

276
00:26:27,918 --> 00:26:30,512
You’re good working on
small engines and things.

277
00:26:30,588 --> 00:26:34,786
If I was to put my neck out
for you with him…

278
00:26:34,892 --> 00:26:37,725
do you think you could work it
if he’ll hire you?

279
00:26:39,930 --> 00:26:43,889
I’m pretty handy, I reckon,
on lawn mowers and whatnot.

280
00:26:43,968 --> 00:26:46,937
I know you are.
I’ve seen it myself.

281
00:26:47,004 --> 00:26:49,666
– Could you give it a try?
– I reckon.

282
00:26:51,675 --> 00:26:54,906
Now I can’t promise
that he’ll hire you.

283
00:26:54,979 --> 00:26:57,209
I’ll have to tell him
about your history.

284
00:26:59,016 --> 00:27:02,008
I never was no good with history.

285
00:27:02,119 --> 00:27:04,519
No. I mean your past.

286
00:27:07,391 --> 00:27:09,416
Why you were in here.

287
00:27:10,861 --> 00:27:13,295
Take you down first thing
in the morning.

288
00:27:14,999 --> 00:27:17,297
You don’t have
anywhere to stay tonight at all?

289
00:27:18,469 --> 00:27:19,493
No, sir.

290
00:27:19,570 --> 00:27:21,868
It’s against the rules
for you to stay here.

291
00:27:21,939 --> 00:27:25,033
If something happened,
I’d be liable.

292
00:27:27,678 --> 00:27:32,308
I reckon I can walk around till
morning time, sit and read a book.

293
00:27:50,768 --> 00:27:53,601
Karl, would you like
a muffin?

294
00:27:53,671 --> 00:27:55,605
No, thank you.

295
00:27:59,343 --> 00:28:02,744
So Jerry’s taking you
someplace else tomorrow.

296
00:28:04,248 --> 00:28:06,716
I don’t know nobody named Jerry.

297
00:28:07,751 --> 00:28:10,117
That’s me, Karl. That’s my first name.

298
00:28:11,722 --> 00:28:14,247
He’s carrying me to look for work
down in Millsburg…

299
00:28:14,358 --> 00:28:16,292
where I was born.

300
00:28:18,896 --> 00:28:20,830
Would you like some coffee?

301
00:28:20,898 --> 00:28:25,028
Coffee makes me a mite nervous
when I drink it.

302
00:28:25,636 --> 00:28:27,433
Daddy, can I go to bed?

303
00:28:27,504 --> 00:28:30,530
Sure. You sleep
with your mama tonight.

304
00:28:30,607 --> 00:28:33,576
I’m sleeping with your brother
so Karl can have your room.

305
00:28:33,644 --> 00:28:35,134
Why?

306
00:28:36,580 --> 00:28:38,571
Because he’s company.

307
00:28:50,828 --> 00:28:53,353
– Karl, you up?
– Yes, sir.

308
00:28:58,102 --> 00:28:59,467
Didn’t you sleep?

309
00:28:59,536 --> 00:29:02,300
You been sitting there
like that all night?

310
00:29:02,372 --> 00:29:04,431
Yes, sir.

311
00:29:04,508 --> 00:29:06,533
Come on. We’d better hit the road.

312
00:29:07,644 --> 00:29:10,044
All right, then.

313
00:30:03,033 --> 00:30:04,967
Jerry, how’s it going?

314
00:30:05,035 --> 00:30:07,299
– Hey, Bill.
– Good to see you.

315
00:30:07,371 --> 00:30:10,932
– Good to see you. How’s everyone doing?
– Pretty good.

316
00:30:11,008 --> 00:30:13,704
Kids are driving me crazy, and Phyliss
is putting me in the poor house…

317
00:30:13,777 --> 00:30:15,506
but I can’t complain otherwise.

318
00:30:15,579 --> 00:30:18,514
Wouldn’t do any good anyway.
You know Scooter?

319
00:30:18,582 --> 00:30:20,709
Don’t believe I do.
Good to meet you, Scooter.

320
00:30:20,784 --> 00:30:23,116
How about you?

321
00:30:23,187 --> 00:30:25,655
Well, this is the one I was
telling you about on the phone.

322
00:30:25,722 --> 00:30:29,590
If you get nervous, I’ll understand,
but I’m not going to lie to you.

323
00:30:29,660 --> 00:30:31,787
He got into that trouble,
but he was young.

324
00:30:31,862 --> 00:30:36,299
I remember. He cut them
to pieces, and one was his mama.

325
00:30:36,366 --> 00:30:38,300
And that Dixon boy.

326
00:30:38,368 --> 00:30:42,270
Hell, I always wanted to kill him.
He was an asshole.

327
00:30:42,339 --> 00:30:44,398
I remember him too.

328
00:30:44,474 --> 00:30:47,739
Kinda retarded or something
back in school.

329
00:30:47,811 --> 00:30:51,872
Seems like he’s pretty
well-adjusted these days.

330
00:30:51,949 --> 00:30:54,281
I don’t think he’d ever hurt anybody.

331
00:30:54,351 --> 00:30:59,550
He don’t look much like he would.
And he can fix a small engine real good?

332
00:30:59,623 --> 00:31:02,251
He’s a whiz. It’s all he’s done
since he was a kid.

333
00:31:02,359 --> 00:31:06,523
– You scared of him, Scooter?
– No, I don’t guess so.

334
00:31:06,597 --> 00:31:08,724
– Can he talk?
– Oh, yeah.

335
00:31:08,799 --> 00:31:11,495
You say he can stay
out in the back?

336
00:31:11,568 --> 00:31:13,536
Fine with me. If he steals anything…

337
00:31:13,604 --> 00:31:15,629
I’ll take it out of your pocket.

338
00:31:15,706 --> 00:31:19,301
He won’t steal. He’s a good old boy.
Keeps to himself.

339
00:31:19,376 --> 00:31:22,573
I got a room full of work.
Scooter won’t do it.

340
00:31:24,081 --> 00:31:26,015
Karl, come over here.

341
00:31:26,083 --> 00:31:28,278
I want you to meet your new boss.

342
00:31:28,352 --> 00:31:31,219
This is Bill Cox.
He runs the place.

343
00:31:31,288 --> 00:31:33,950
Says you can work here,
stay out back.

344
00:31:34,057 --> 00:31:37,493
– It’s good to know you, Karl.
– Thank you.

345
00:31:37,594 --> 00:31:42,327
It’s minimum wage. There’s nothing back
there but an army cot and a toilet.

346
00:31:42,399 --> 00:31:45,664
That’s fine. I’ll go to the car
and get your books.

347
00:31:45,736 --> 00:31:47,704
All right, then.

348
00:31:50,908 --> 00:31:53,843
They say you’re a whiz on fixing
lawn mowers and things.

349
00:31:55,412 --> 00:31:59,314
I’ve tinkered around
on them a bit.

350
00:31:59,383 --> 00:32:02,477
We order from the Frosty Cream
at lunch, usually.

351
00:32:02,552 --> 00:32:05,020
We’ll buy you lunch
till you get on your feet.

352
00:32:06,423 --> 00:32:08,653
I like them
French fried potatoes.

353
00:32:10,694 --> 00:32:12,628
Yeah. Me too.

354
00:32:14,998 --> 00:32:17,592
They make a good double meat burger.

355
00:32:31,114 --> 00:32:33,378
All right, then.
I’ll see y’all later.

356
00:32:33,450 --> 00:32:36,908
Karl, you done good work.
They was right about you.

357
00:32:36,987 --> 00:32:40,445
Scooter, he’s gonna knock you out of
a job if you’re not careful.

358
00:32:40,557 --> 00:32:42,718
– I’ll see y’all tomorrow.
– Wait up.

359
00:32:42,826 --> 00:32:44,760
I’ll leave with you and lock up.

360
00:32:46,663 --> 00:32:51,362
There’s a blanket under the cot, soap
in the bathroom for cleaning up.

361
00:32:51,435 --> 00:32:55,496
One more thing. The way we lock
these doors, you can’t get out at night.

362
00:32:55,572 --> 00:32:59,201
– Did you want to go anywhere?
– I don’t reckon.

363
00:32:59,276 --> 00:33:03,076
If it works out, we’ll get you a key so
you can get out at night.

364
00:33:03,146 --> 00:33:05,341
– I’ll see you later.
– All right, then.

365
00:33:28,972 --> 00:33:32,408
Did I tell you the one about the two
old boys pissing off the bridge?

366
00:33:32,476 --> 00:33:33,943
I don’t remember.

367
00:33:34,011 --> 00:33:38,971
These two old boys hung their peckers
off a bridge to piss.

368
00:33:39,049 --> 00:33:42,450
One was from California,
one from Arkansas.

369
00:33:42,519 --> 00:33:45,682
Old boy from California says,
“Boy, this water’s cold.”

370
00:33:45,756 --> 00:33:48,520
Old boy from Arkansas says,
“Yeah, and it’s deep too.”

371
00:33:52,029 --> 00:33:53,758
Get it?

372
00:33:53,830 --> 00:33:57,288
– Yeah, that’s a good one.
– That is a good one.

373
00:33:57,367 --> 00:34:01,861
I do believe you told me that before.
I’ve heard it a bunch.

374
00:34:01,972 --> 00:34:06,136
– A long time ago.
– Yeah, that’s a classic.

375
00:34:06,209 --> 00:34:11,579
Karl, I’ve been thinking, and it’s not
Christian of me to keep locking you in.

376
00:34:11,648 --> 00:34:14,446
You’ve been in lockup so long,
you don’t need me to keep doing it.

377
00:34:14,518 --> 00:34:17,009
You need to come and go as you please.
Here.

378
00:34:18,688 --> 00:34:21,623
Take this key. It’ll get you
in and out of here at night.

379
00:34:24,561 --> 00:34:26,426
All right, then.

380
00:34:28,665 --> 00:34:32,066
– Them French fries good?
– They’s good, all right.

381
00:34:34,204 --> 00:34:36,138
You got any money?

382
00:34:37,374 --> 00:34:39,842
They give me some
when they turned me loose.

383
00:34:41,711 --> 00:34:45,477
I spent some riding the bus,
eating French fried potatoes.

384
00:34:47,484 --> 00:34:50,976
I’m going to pay you today
for this coming week…

385
00:34:51,054 --> 00:34:53,579
so you have some walking-around money.

386
00:34:53,657 --> 00:34:58,560
You need to buy some toothpaste and
cleaning up supplies to have back there.

387
00:34:58,628 --> 00:35:02,120
Get you some magazines
and some hard candy…

388
00:35:02,232 --> 00:35:05,827
something to keep you busy
at night.

389
00:35:05,936 --> 00:35:07,904
All right, then.

390
00:35:07,971 --> 00:35:10,303
I’ll let you off
while it’s still daylight.

391
00:35:42,806 --> 00:35:47,266
I thought I heard somebody on the porch.
Wasn’t your name Karl?

392
00:35:48,945 --> 00:35:52,312
Yes, sir, it is.
You’re named Frank.

393
00:35:53,016 --> 00:35:56,349
Yeah. What are you doing by here?

394
00:35:56,419 --> 00:36:00,150
– You said for me to come by.
– Wanna play ball with us?

395
00:36:01,057 --> 00:36:05,357
I ain’t no good at it.
I just come by to see you.

396
00:36:05,428 --> 00:36:10,331
I was going to see my mama at Hoochy’s
Dollar Store. She works 2:00 to 8:00.

397
00:36:10,867 --> 00:36:13,597
All right, then.

398
00:36:13,670 --> 00:36:16,161
You want to go with me?
You can meet my mama.

399
00:36:18,341 --> 00:36:20,832
I ought not worry your mama
with company.

400
00:36:20,944 --> 00:36:24,937
Come on. You’ll like her.
She’s real nice.

401
00:36:25,015 --> 00:36:28,746
She’ll give us anything we want her to,
candy or something.

402
00:36:30,487 --> 00:36:33,422
I was needing to do some trading.

403
00:36:33,490 --> 00:36:35,685
Reckon they sell toothpaste?

404
00:36:35,759 --> 00:36:38,922
Yeah, they sell a little bit
of everything.

405
00:36:38,995 --> 00:36:43,056
I won’t tell her about you being in
the state hospital for killing.

406
00:36:43,166 --> 00:36:45,100
Come on. Let’s go.

407
00:37:00,250 --> 00:37:03,185
You have to learn to live
without all that grease.

408
00:37:03,253 --> 00:37:06,518
Here in the South,
I like grease in everything.

409
00:37:06,590 --> 00:37:10,253
I like fried chicken, fried okra,
biscuits and gravy.

410
00:37:10,327 --> 00:37:12,124
– It will kill you.
– Hey, Mama, Vaughan.

411
00:37:12,229 --> 00:37:14,629
– What you up to, sweetheart?
– I bet I know.

412
00:37:14,698 --> 00:37:17,428
– You want candy and pop, right?
– Yeah.

413
00:37:17,500 --> 00:37:20,799
That rots your teeth.
I’ve got something better.

414
00:37:20,870 --> 00:37:23,338
Potted meat is on special –
four cans for a dollar.

415
00:37:23,406 --> 00:37:28,901
They’re not selling but I’ll give
the right kid some for free.

416
00:37:28,979 --> 00:37:30,913
I don’t like potted meat.

417
00:37:30,981 --> 00:37:34,348
Daddy said it was made from lips,
peckers and intestines.

418
00:37:34,417 --> 00:37:38,615
Don’t talk that way. Did that
strange-looking man follow you in here?

419
00:37:40,457 --> 00:37:41,856
Can I help you?

420
00:37:42,525 --> 00:37:46,154
That’s Karl. I met him
at the laundry mat.

421
00:37:46,229 --> 00:37:48,891
Karl, this is Mama and Vaughan.

422
00:37:48,999 --> 00:37:51,058
Vaughan is the manager.

423
00:37:51,167 --> 00:37:55,365
He lets Mama off work anytime
because they’re best friends.

424
00:37:55,438 --> 00:37:57,372
Nice to meet you, Karl.

425
00:37:58,808 --> 00:38:00,799
Pleased to meet you.

426
00:38:04,114 --> 00:38:07,515
Frank, come back here with me
for a minute.

427
00:38:13,356 --> 00:38:15,381
I haven’t seen you here before.

428
00:38:16,760 --> 00:38:20,719
No, sir, I don’t reckon you have.
I haven’t been in here before.

429
00:38:20,830 --> 00:38:24,266
This store didn’t used to be here.

430
00:38:24,367 --> 00:38:28,701
It’s been here 17 years.
Did you live here before?

431
00:38:28,772 --> 00:38:31,673
I was born and raised here till
I was 12 years old.

432
00:38:33,009 --> 00:38:36,342
– What brings you back?
– What’s that you say?

433
00:38:38,415 --> 00:38:41,407
Why are you here now?

434
00:38:41,484 --> 00:38:44,351
They turned me loose from
the state hospital.

435
00:38:44,421 --> 00:38:49,085
Is that right?
How long are you staying?

436
00:38:49,159 --> 00:38:53,687
Mr. Woolridge got me hired
at Bill Cox’s outfit.

437
00:38:54,864 --> 00:38:57,697
– You have family here?
– Not to speak of.

438
00:38:57,801 --> 00:39:02,397
Hey, Karl. Guess what?
Mama said you can stay in our garage.

439
00:39:02,505 --> 00:39:05,702
Our car doesn’t fit anyway.
It’s real neat.

440
00:39:05,775 --> 00:39:09,370
Frank told me about your situation.
Frank loves company.

441
00:39:09,446 --> 00:39:11,914
Especially after his daddy passed
and all.

442
00:39:11,981 --> 00:39:15,473
There’s no sense in you staying
in that greasy old shop.

443
00:39:15,552 --> 00:39:17,816
He’s mentally retarded,
poor thing.

444
00:39:17,887 --> 00:39:20,651
– He just go out of the state hospital.
– I know.

445
00:39:20,724 --> 00:39:23,386
– Can we get some candy and pop?
– Sure. Go ahead.

446
00:39:23,460 --> 00:39:25,428
Come on.

447
00:39:26,663 --> 00:39:30,724
– Is it safe to let him around that guy?
– Frank’s crazy about him.

448
00:39:30,834 --> 00:39:34,770
He likes the way he talks and he helped
Frank carry home the laundry.

449
00:39:34,871 --> 00:39:38,238
He’s been in the hospital a long time.
There must be something wrong with him.

450
00:39:38,308 --> 00:39:41,436
He’s retarded. Frank’s always after
a father figure.

451
00:39:41,511 --> 00:39:43,809
Lord knows Doyle ain’t a good one
with his mean ass.

452
00:39:43,880 --> 00:39:47,611
– What about me?
– He doesn’t see you as a “guy” guy.

453
00:39:47,684 --> 00:39:49,709
Karl’s a “guy” guy?

454
00:40:08,772 --> 00:40:10,974
I call this my secret place.

455
00:40:10,974 --> 00:40:14,341
I come out here when I feel like
being alone.

456
00:40:14,411 --> 00:40:16,470
I used to come here with Karen Cross.

457
00:40:16,579 --> 00:40:20,379
She kind of used to be my girlfriend.

458
00:40:20,483 --> 00:40:23,452
We would come out here
and hold hands and talk…

459
00:40:23,520 --> 00:40:26,887
and read books to each other
with a flashlight.

460
00:40:26,923 --> 00:40:29,756
She wouldn’t have nothing to do with me
in front of other people…

461
00:40:29,826 --> 00:40:33,853
because Mama and I
don’t have any money.

462
00:40:33,930 --> 00:40:36,899
Her daddy’s a dentist,
so they’re rich.

463
00:40:37,634 --> 00:40:40,228
Was your folks well off?

464
00:40:40,303 --> 00:40:44,933
No, we barely had enough
to scrape by on, I reckon.

465
00:40:45,008 --> 00:40:47,841
Your folks still around?

466
00:40:47,911 --> 00:40:49,845
My mother’s dead.

467
00:40:49,946 --> 00:40:54,440
My daddy’s still around but he don’t
want to have nothing to do with me.

468
00:40:54,551 --> 00:40:58,248
– How do you know?
– He never did want to.

469
00:40:58,354 --> 00:41:02,222
I figure he probably
ain’t changed his mind much.

470
00:41:02,292 --> 00:41:04,226
How’d your mama die?

471
00:41:06,830 --> 00:41:09,094
You don’t need to hear
things like that.

472
