01:13:09,926 --> 01:13:14,864
There was these two fellers standing
on a bridge going to the bathroom.

941
01:13:17,070 --> 01:13:21,234
One feller says that the water is cold.

942
01:13:21,343 --> 01:13:23,743
The other says that the water is deep.

943
01:13:27,651 --> 01:13:30,176
I believe one feller comes from
Arkansas.

944
01:13:31,290 --> 01:13:33,223
Get it?

945
01:13:34,929 --> 01:13:36,919
I’ll be dog.

946
01:13:49,348 --> 01:13:52,875
Reckon you can make some biscuits?

947
01:13:52,954 --> 01:13:55,650
You mean right now?

948
01:13:55,724 --> 01:13:59,319
Whenever you take a notion to.
I don’t mean to put you out none.

949
01:14:00,630 --> 01:14:03,326
It is nearly breakfast time anyway.

950
01:14:03,400 --> 01:14:07,029
I can’t go to sleep.
I have to be at work in three hours.

951
01:14:07,106 --> 01:14:09,506
You know how it is if you only sleep
an hour or two.

952
01:14:09,576 --> 01:14:12,602
You feel worse than if you hadn’t
slept at all.

953
01:14:12,680 --> 01:14:14,613
Yes, ma’am. I do.

954
01:14:16,919 --> 01:14:20,548
Sit down.
I’ll make you some biscuits and gravy.

955
01:14:20,625 --> 01:14:24,186
– Mustard’s good on them to me.
– Okay.

956
01:14:24,263 --> 01:14:28,097
– Thank you.
– It’s all right.

957
01:14:30,171 --> 01:14:34,369
I was thinking –
There’s this girl that works with me.

958
01:14:34,443 --> 01:14:37,344
She’s real heavy,
but she’s cute in the face.

959
01:14:37,414 --> 01:14:40,906
Well, you know, she’s slow.

960
01:14:42,488 --> 01:14:47,153
She’s a little bit –
She’s not retarded.

961
01:14:47,229 --> 01:14:50,494
It don’t matter.
I thought you might like to meet her.

962
01:14:50,566 --> 01:14:53,831
Vaughan wants to have a supper at his
house. We could invite her.

963
01:14:53,903 --> 01:14:56,029
Would you like that?

964
01:14:57,142 --> 01:15:00,703
I reckon I wouldn’t mind
having a little supper.

965
01:15:00,814 --> 01:15:04,250
Vaughan’s friend will be there too.
He works at the funeral home.

966
01:15:06,588 --> 01:15:08,954
You know, Frank really likes you a lot.

967
01:15:09,025 --> 01:15:11,755
He says you make him feel calm.

968
01:15:11,828 --> 01:15:15,264
I like Frank.
He’s a good boy.

969
01:15:15,334 --> 01:15:17,962
Me and him made friends.

970
01:15:25,247 --> 01:15:27,180
It ain’t right for me to keep
from telling you…

971
01:15:27,250 --> 01:15:29,775
how come me to be in a state hospital.

972
01:15:31,356 --> 01:15:34,154
That’s okay.
It’s not really my business.

973
01:15:35,795 --> 01:15:38,355
Have wondered, though.

974
01:15:38,466 --> 01:15:42,266
Why was it?
Was it like a nervous breakdown?

975
01:15:48,580 --> 01:15:53,074
I killed my mother
and an old boy named Jesse Dixon.

976
01:15:53,153 --> 01:15:55,621
I thought they’s doing wrong.

977
01:15:56,557 --> 01:15:59,253
I was about your boy’s age.

978
01:15:59,328 --> 01:16:01,386
They told me I’m well from it now.

979
01:16:01,464 --> 01:16:03,397
Was that you?

980
01:16:03,467 --> 01:16:05,992
I remember that.
I was only three or four…

981
01:16:06,070 --> 01:16:08,470
but I always heard about it
growing up.

982
01:16:08,541 --> 01:16:11,135
They say you’re well?

983
01:16:11,245 --> 01:16:13,178
Yes, ma’am.

984
01:16:19,891 --> 01:16:22,051
I like your garage.

985
01:16:26,131 --> 01:16:29,464
I never would hurt you or that boy.

986
01:16:29,537 --> 01:16:33,633
I’d lay my hand on the Bible
and say the same thing.

987
01:16:33,709 --> 01:16:36,041
I know you wouldn’t, hon.

988
01:16:43,355 --> 01:16:45,880
Well, I’ll make you some biscuits.

989
01:17:00,445 --> 01:17:02,173
How about you, Jerry?

990
01:17:02,248 --> 01:17:04,648
– How are you, Bill?
– Doing pretty good.

991
01:17:04,718 --> 01:17:08,176
Got a sick tiller.
What’s got you down this way?

992
01:17:08,290 --> 01:17:10,952
I thought I’d check up on Karl.
See how things are working out.

993
01:17:11,027 --> 01:17:14,554
He’s pretty quiet, except for them
rackets and breathing things he does.

994
01:17:14,633 --> 01:17:16,965
He ain’t threatening me
with a killing or nothing.

995
01:17:17,035 --> 01:17:19,333
You couldn’t have been more right
about him fixing things.

996
01:17:19,405 --> 01:17:22,067
He’s a regular Eli Whitney
on a lawn mower.

997
01:17:22,142 --> 01:17:26,773
And loves French fries. He can eat
four larges and won’t even belch.

998
01:17:26,849 --> 01:17:28,713
I’m proud to have him.

999
01:17:28,785 --> 01:17:31,652
– Him staying working out?
– He’s gone to staying with…

1000
01:17:31,756 --> 01:17:34,156
that Wheatley boy and his mama
in their garage.

1001
01:17:34,260 --> 01:17:37,161
That little boy’s adopted
him like a mascot.

1002
01:17:37,230 --> 01:17:39,494
He got a key here
to come and go as he pleases.

1003
01:17:39,567 --> 01:17:41,431
He’s working out real good.

1004
01:17:41,503 --> 01:17:43,060
– Can I see him?
– Sure.

1005
01:17:43,171 --> 01:17:45,537
Scooter, take Jerry in
to talk to Karl.

1006
01:17:45,608 --> 01:17:47,541
All right.

1007
01:17:52,819 --> 01:17:55,947
Sure you’ll be okay
staying with that woman and her boy?

1008
01:17:56,023 --> 01:17:57,956
Yes, sir.

1009
01:17:58,026 --> 01:18:00,824
Do they know about you?

1010
01:18:00,896 --> 01:18:02,829
My history?

1011
01:18:02,899 --> 01:18:04,729
Yeah.

1012
01:18:04,802 --> 01:18:07,362
I told them about it.

1013
01:18:09,576 --> 01:18:11,908
They know I’m well.

1014
01:18:12,980 --> 01:18:15,346
That Miss Wheatley
made me some biscuits.

1015
01:18:16,418 --> 01:18:18,750
I’ll be.

1016
01:18:18,821 --> 01:18:22,313
That boy, he’s my friend.

1017
01:18:22,393 --> 01:18:25,487
He likes the way I talk,
and I like the way he talks.

1018
01:18:27,400 --> 01:18:29,264
I knew you were gonna be all right.

1019
01:18:29,336 --> 01:18:31,896
I just wanna check on you.

1020
01:18:31,973 --> 01:18:35,875
I’m gonna tell Bill good-bye
and head on back.

1021
01:18:35,979 --> 01:18:37,878
All right, then.

1022
01:18:42,788 --> 01:18:45,450
Karl, see if you can
figure out what’s wrong with this thing.

1023
01:18:45,525 --> 01:18:48,756
It won’t crank up. Everything seems
to be put together right.

1024
01:18:48,829 --> 01:18:51,354
– Bill, I’ll see you.
– Okay. Stop back by.

1025
01:18:51,433 --> 01:18:54,561
Don’t worry about your boy.
He’s doing good.

1026
01:18:55,438 --> 01:18:58,635
It ain’t got no gas in it.

1027
01:18:58,710 --> 01:19:02,510
You see there, Scooter.
Thinks of the simplest things first.

1028
01:19:03,951 --> 01:19:07,580
– Does everybody like the food?
– Yeah.

1029
01:19:07,656 --> 01:19:10,921
Good. I haven’t decided yet
if I’m a good cook.

1030
01:19:13,330 --> 01:19:15,058
Karl, you know what?

1031
01:19:15,166 --> 01:19:19,934
Melinda was voted employee of the month
at the Dollar Store last February.

1032
01:19:20,006 --> 01:19:22,736
Isn’t that something?

1033
01:19:22,810 --> 01:19:24,936
Yes, ma’am. I reckon.

1034
01:19:25,012 --> 01:19:28,743
When you like pricing items
as much as I do…

1035
01:19:28,818 --> 01:19:32,447
it’s just bound to happen
sooner or later, I guess.

1036
01:19:34,393 --> 01:19:39,297
Maybe you and Melinda
might like to take a walk tonight.

1037
01:19:39,367 --> 01:19:42,359
– It’s such a nice evening.
– Vaughan, don’t get pushy.

1038
01:19:42,470 --> 01:19:44,562
I’m sorry.

1039
01:19:45,742 --> 01:19:49,041
I kind of like walking
from time to time.

1040
01:19:49,113 --> 01:19:51,877
I stay on my feet all the time at work.

1041
01:19:51,983 --> 01:19:55,419
I just can’t find shoes
that’s comfortable.

1042
01:19:55,489 --> 01:19:59,687
Hospital shoes might be the answer.
Nurse’s shoes.

1043
01:19:59,762 --> 01:20:02,322
Or the kind old ladies wear
who work in school cafeterias.

1044
01:20:02,398 --> 01:20:05,196
Same difference.

1045
01:20:05,268 --> 01:20:07,998
I get real mean when my feet hurt.

1046
01:20:08,073 --> 01:20:11,440
It’s the only time
I don’t like checking out customers.

1047
01:20:11,511 --> 01:20:14,036
When my feet hurt.

1048
01:20:14,115 --> 01:20:16,549
You and Karl aren’t talking much.

1049
01:20:16,618 --> 01:20:19,451
You boys must really like that food.

1050
01:20:19,522 --> 01:20:22,650
Well, I ain’t got nothing to say
about shoes.

1051
01:20:22,760 --> 01:20:25,160
Listen, everybody.

1052
01:20:25,230 --> 01:20:28,028
This might sound corny, but –

1053
01:20:29,436 --> 01:20:32,371
I’ve had some wine
and that tends to make me emotional…

1054
01:20:32,440 --> 01:20:34,430
but I’m gonna say it anyway.

1055
01:20:34,510 --> 01:20:37,138
It came over me in a rush.

1056
01:20:37,212 --> 01:20:39,703
I just want you all to know…

1057
01:20:39,784 --> 01:20:44,916
that I care about
each and every person at this table.

1058
01:20:44,991 --> 01:20:47,151
Thank you.
That’s really sweet of you.

1059
01:20:47,227 --> 01:20:49,491
We care about you too.
Don’t we, y’all?

1060
01:20:49,597 --> 01:20:51,029
Yeah.

1061
01:20:51,100 --> 01:20:56,004
Also, please don’t tell anyone
at the store…

1062
01:20:56,072 --> 01:20:58,198
that Albert was here tonight.

1063
01:21:02,949 --> 01:21:04,745
Why?

1064
01:21:04,819 --> 01:21:07,310
You know how this town is.
People talk…

1065
01:21:07,389 --> 01:21:10,790
and they spread cruel rumours.

1066
01:21:10,860 --> 01:21:16,163
Unfortunately, there’s certain parts
of my life I have to keep private.

1067
01:21:16,234 --> 01:21:21,002
You mean about you and Albert
being together in that way?

1068
01:21:21,074 --> 01:21:24,532
– Yes.
– I think everybody already knows.

1069
01:21:24,579 --> 01:21:26,979
They’re always talking about it.

1070
01:21:27,049 --> 01:21:30,348
Maureen Ledbetter told
the most awful story…

1071
01:21:30,420 --> 01:21:33,981
about why you ain’t allowed
at the First Baptist Church no more.

1072
01:21:34,092 --> 01:21:37,687
Karl, why don’t you and Melinda
take a walk? It’s nice out.

1073
01:21:44,340 --> 01:21:46,604
All right, then.

1074
01:21:55,955 --> 01:21:57,922
That sure was quick.

1075
01:22:05,402 --> 01:22:07,335
You walk fast, don’t you?

1076
01:22:07,404 --> 01:22:09,303
I reckon.

1077
01:22:11,076 --> 01:22:13,544
These are the worst shoes I own
for walking.

1078
01:22:14,615 --> 01:22:17,413
How far’d you say you want to go?

1079
01:22:17,486 --> 01:22:21,183
I don’t reckon
I thought about it too much.

1080
01:22:22,493 --> 01:22:23,226
I don’t know.
She just ain’t catching fire.

1081
01:22:23,227 --> 01:22:26,219
I don’t know.
She just ain’t catching fire.

1082
01:22:26,298 --> 01:22:28,527
Did you check them points?

1083
01:22:29,602 --> 01:22:32,127
No, I didn’t.

1084
01:22:32,205 --> 01:22:34,503
That’s probably it.

1085
01:22:36,245 --> 01:22:38,713
– Yes, ma’am?
– Is Karl here?

1086
01:22:38,782 --> 01:22:40,908
Yes. Just a minute.

1087
01:22:44,056 --> 01:22:46,547
Karl. There’s somebody out here
to see you.

1088
01:22:46,626 --> 01:22:49,595
Some gal holding a nice bouquet.

1089
01:22:49,663 --> 01:22:54,100
Come on out. She wants to talk to you.
Don’t just sit there.

1090
01:23:07,855 --> 01:23:11,621
Hi. I’m on my lunch break.

1091
01:23:11,694 --> 01:23:13,627
These are on sale
’cause they’re not fresh.

1092
01:23:14,598 --> 01:23:19,901
Two ninety-nine a bunch, plus
my ten percent employee discount.

1093
01:23:19,971 --> 01:23:24,534
Since I didn’t bring nothing for you
on our date last night…

1094
01:23:24,611 --> 01:23:27,045
I thought you might like to have them.

1095
01:23:35,060 --> 01:23:37,027
Thank you.

1096
01:23:37,062 --> 01:23:40,828
Scooter, let’s go over to the Frosty
Cream and pick up something for lunch.

1097
01:23:40,934 --> 01:23:42,662
I can go.
You don’t have to.

1098
01:23:42,771 --> 01:23:45,604
– You don’t never go.
– Goddammit, Scooter. Let’s go.

1099
01:23:46,675 --> 01:23:48,608
Pardon my language, ma’am.

1100
01:24:04,634 --> 01:24:07,694
Well, I just thought I’d bring them.

1101
01:24:08,773 --> 01:24:10,967
I liked walking with you.

1102
01:24:11,077 --> 01:24:14,376
I got a blister the size of a quarter
on one heel.

1103
01:24:16,717 --> 01:24:20,380
Well, I’ll see you sometime, I guess.

1104
01:24:26,431 --> 01:24:28,831
Blisters sure can hurt.

1105
01:24:31,071 --> 01:24:32,503
Yeah.

1106
01:24:36,878 --> 01:24:38,868
Flowers is pretty.

1107
01:24:38,948 --> 01:24:41,280
I’ve always thought that.

1108
01:24:44,123 --> 01:24:46,056
Me too.

1109
01:25:36,295 --> 01:25:39,594
Hey, Karl.
How’d you know I was in the garage?

1110
01:25:39,666 --> 01:25:44,969
I seen that door cracked open a little.
I figured you was in there.

1111
01:25:45,040 --> 01:25:47,565
– You off of work?
– Yes, sir.

1112
01:25:47,643 --> 01:25:50,373
Where’d you get them flowers?

1113
01:25:50,447 --> 01:25:53,780
That gal that made employee of the month
at the Dollar Store.

1114
01:25:53,852 --> 01:25:56,844
She gave them to me
for walking with her.

1115
01:25:58,359 --> 01:26:00,793
I was going over to the secret place.

1116
01:26:00,862 --> 01:26:04,059
I borrowed one of your books.
You ain’t mad, are you?

1117
01:26:04,132 --> 01:26:07,033
No, sir. You can look at every one
of my books you want to.

1118
01:26:07,103 --> 01:26:10,436
Thank you.
It’s name’s “A Christmas Carol.”

1119
01:26:10,508 --> 01:26:13,500
That’s that one on Christmas
I was telling you about.

1120
01:26:14,581 --> 01:26:16,514
You wanna go with me?

1121
01:26:17,585 --> 01:26:19,518
All right, then.

1122
01:26:19,588 --> 01:26:21,954
– Yeah. Come on.
– All right.

1123
01:26:29,868 --> 01:26:32,028
Know why I want you
to play ball with me?

1124
01:26:32,138 --> 01:26:33,570
No.

1125
01:26:33,641 --> 01:26:37,042
’Cause it’s fun.
Don’t matter if you ain’t no good.

1126
01:26:37,113 --> 01:26:39,775
It takes your mind
off of everything else.

1127
01:26:39,882 --> 01:26:42,612
And when you’re trying to score
a touchdown…

1128
01:26:42,686 --> 01:26:44,778
that’s all you’re thinking about.

1129
01:26:44,856 --> 01:26:48,053
I ain’t no account,
but Daddy always said…

1130
01:26:48,128 --> 01:26:52,189
he was proud of me when I threw the ball
and ran with it.

1131
01:26:52,266 --> 01:26:56,703
Did you have any brothers and sisters
growing up to play with?

1132
01:26:56,772 --> 01:26:59,764
I had one there for a little bit.

1133
01:26:59,843 --> 01:27:01,207
But…

1134
01:27:02,314 --> 01:27:05,283
it didn’t get old enough
for me to play with it.

1135
01:27:05,384 --> 01:27:07,818
Why not? It die?

1136
01:27:07,921 --> 01:27:09,820
Yes, sir.

1137
01:27:09,891 --> 01:27:11,323
Why?

1138
01:27:12,394 --> 01:27:15,022
It got born a little too early.

1139
01:27:15,097 --> 01:27:19,694
My mother and father
made it come out too early.

1140
01:27:20,772 --> 01:27:23,138
So it died when it come out?

1141
01:27:24,545 --> 01:27:28,481
My daddy come out to the shed
and got me…

1142
01:27:28,550 --> 01:27:30,483
said, “Here. Take this
and throw it away.”

1143
01:27:30,553 --> 01:27:33,886
He handed me a towel
with something or another in it.

1144
01:27:37,095 --> 01:27:39,028
I started for that barrel…

1145
01:27:40,600 --> 01:27:44,297
and I opened up the towel
’cause there was a noise…

1146
01:27:44,372 --> 01:27:46,498
and something moving around in it.

1147
01:27:48,378 --> 01:27:52,405
That towel was all bloody-like
all around it there.

1148
01:27:57,189 --> 01:28:01,387
It was a little old baby,
not no bigger than a squirrel.

1149
01:28:02,263 --> 01:28:04,321
It was alive?

1150
01:28:04,400 --> 01:28:07,028
Yes, sir.
Right then it was.

1151
01:28:08,738 --> 01:28:10,295
A boy or girl?

1152
01:28:11,609 --> 01:28:14,043
It was a little old boy.

1153
01:28:15,882 --> 01:28:18,350
You threw it in the trash barrel?

1154
01:28:19,220 --> 01:28:21,984
That didn’t seem right to me.

1155
01:28:22,057 --> 01:28:24,355
So I went into the shed
and got a shoe box…

1156
01:28:24,428 --> 01:28:27,090
and emptied out the screwdrivers,
washers and nuts…

1157
01:28:27,164 --> 01:28:29,028
and things out of it.

1158
01:28:30,335 --> 01:28:33,532
I taken the little feller
and put him in the box…

1159
01:28:33,606 --> 01:28:36,598
buried him in the corner of the yard.

1160
01:28:36,678 --> 01:28:40,045
That seemed more proper to me,
I reckon.

1161
01:28:40,983 --> 01:28:43,281
It was still alive when you buried it?

1162
01:28:44,622 --> 01:28:47,420
I heard it crying a little
through that box.

1163
01:28:52,600 --> 01:28:56,434
That don’t seem right. It seems like
you would have took care of him…

1164
01:28:56,505 --> 01:28:58,597
if he was your brother.

1165
01:28:58,675 --> 01:29:00,801
I wasn’t but six or eight.

1166
01:29:00,878 --> 01:29:04,245
I reckon I didn’t know
what to do.

1167
01:29:04,316 --> 01:29:06,510
I didn’t know how to care
for no baby.

1168
01:29:07,687 --> 01:29:10,155
My mother and father didn’t want him.

1169
01:29:11,593 --> 01:29:14,187
They learned me to do
what they told me to do.

1170
01:29:15,799 --> 01:29:19,496
I figure it probably best we give him
right back to the good Lord…

1171
01:29:19,571 --> 01:29:21,663
right off the bat anyhow.

1172
01:29:22,975 --> 01:29:25,876
That makes me feel real sad.

1173
01:29:26,981 --> 01:29:29,141
Couldn’t you have done something?

1174
01:29:29,217 --> 01:29:31,845
I would have.
I wish I’d had him.

1175
01:29:31,921 --> 01:29:35,755
He’d still be right here, now.
Living.

1176
01:29:36,761 --> 01:29:38,785
It makes me sad too.

1177
01:29:40,132 --> 01:29:43,101
I wish there was something
I could have did about it.

1178
01:29:46,140 --> 01:29:49,598
I don’t think nothing bad
oughta happen to children.

1179
01:29:50,713 --> 01:29:53,181
I think all those bad things
oughta be saved up…

1180
01:29:53,284 --> 01:29:58,222
for the folks that done growed up,
that’s the way I see it.

1181
01:30:00,561 --> 01:30:03,621
I shouldn’t have told you about that.

1182
01:30:03,731 --> 01:30:07,223
Boy your age ought not
to hear such things.

1183
01:30:07,304 --> 01:30:09,932
It just kind of come out.

1184
01:30:10,007 --> 01:30:13,135
I didn’t mean to say nothing
bad about you.

1185
01:30:13,211 --> 01:30:17,238
You’re good.
You don’t mean no harm.

1186
01:30:17,317 --> 01:30:21,651
You ever think about killing yourself
on purpose, like Daddy did?

1187
01:30:24,493 --> 01:30:26,757
I studied about it some.

1188
01:30:27,865 --> 01:30:29,923
Bible says you ought not to.

1189
01:30:31,838 --> 01:30:35,171
Says you do that,
you go off to Hades.

1190
01:30:35,241 --> 01:30:38,267
Some folks call it hell.
I call it Hades.

1191
01:30:39,648 --> 01:30:43,243
Bible says the same thing
about killing others too.

1192
01:30:53,166 --> 01:30:55,430
Yes, sir.
I reckon it does.

1193
01:31:12,894 --> 01:31:16,386
Spend more time over here –

1194
01:31:17,401 --> 01:31:19,368
Well, hell.
There’s the boys.

1195
01:31:19,437 --> 01:31:22,133
How you doing?
Glad you all came back.

1196
01:31:23,542 --> 01:31:26,875
I was wanting to talk to y’all.
Come sit down.

1197
01:31:26,947 --> 01:31:28,880
Come on. Sit down.

1198
01:31:28,949 --> 01:31:33,944
I was just telling Linda –
We were thinking that things…

1199
01:31:34,023 --> 01:31:37,925
would be a lot better if I spent
more time over here.

1200
01:31:37,996 --> 01:31:42,764
And if we could –
Hell, I’ll just start over.

1201
01:31:42,836 --> 01:31:47,433
I took off work early today, and your
mama did the same, so we could talk.

1202
01:31:48,543 --> 01:31:51,876
Really what I came over here to do
was apologize –

1203
01:31:51,948 --> 01:31:54,074
which ain’t easy for me –

1204
01:31:54,151 --> 01:31:56,380
about how I acted the other night.

1205
01:31:57,657 --> 01:31:59,385
I admit it.
I was drunk.

1206
01:32:00,661 --> 01:32:04,563
I got all worked up
and one thing led to another.

1207
01:32:05,633 --> 01:32:10,070
I care about you all, though.
I do.

1208
01:32:10,140 --> 01:32:13,871
I don’t mean to be so damned –

1209
01:32:13,946 --> 01:32:16,938
well, asshole-ish,
I guess would be the word.

1210
01:32:18,052 --> 01:32:21,180
Karl, I don’t believe I hit you,
did I?

1211
01:32:21,256 --> 01:32:24,316
So no apology necessary, I guess.

1212
01:32:24,392 --> 01:32:26,724
But, Frankie, I’m sorry.

1213
01:32:26,796 --> 01:32:29,162
I’m sorry I hit your mama.

1214
01:32:30,235 --> 01:32:33,068
It’s just that I’m jealous of her.

1215
01:32:33,139 --> 01:32:36,006
I don’t like her life
or how she lives it.

1216
01:32:37,178 --> 01:32:39,202
I don’t like homosexuals.

1217
01:32:39,314 --> 01:32:43,877
And she goes out and buddies
up with one, so I gotta deal with that.

1218
01:32:43,987 --> 01:32:46,956
I don’t like wimpy-ass kids
or mental retards…

1219
01:32:47,057 --> 01:32:49,457
and she got one of each
living with her.

1220
01:32:51,164 --> 01:32:53,655
I’m just kidding about that.

1221
01:32:55,103 --> 01:32:56,967
I mean, we all got to get along…

1222
01:32:57,039 --> 01:32:59,564
no matter what our differences are.

1223
01:33:00,876 --> 01:33:03,208
See, I work construction.

1224
01:33:03,281 --> 01:33:05,248
I build things.

1225
01:33:05,316 --> 01:33:08,479
You understand how important that is
to the world, Frankie?

1226
01:33:10,090 --> 01:33:14,459
I don’t know if you realize
the pressure a man like me’s got on him.

1227
01:33:15,865 --> 01:33:19,494
The upshot is, I’m gonna be spending
a lot more time here.

1228
01:33:19,603 --> 01:33:22,538
We’re gonna all get along
like a family should.

1229
01:33:24,076 --> 01:33:27,512
I might even surprise you
and pop the question.

1230
01:33:32,321 --> 01:33:34,254
Well.

1231
01:33:34,324 --> 01:33:37,816
I’m gonna get on back over
to the job site…

1232
01:33:37,895 --> 01:33:39,828
lock up some stuff over there.

1233
01:33:39,898 --> 01:33:45,804
I just wanted to stop by and give y’all
a little piece of happiness today.

1234
01:33:45,873 --> 01:33:47,134
Bye-bye.

1235
01:33:53,250 --> 01:33:55,844
You be a good boy now.
Hear me?

1236
01:34:02,663 --> 01:34:06,360
Well, at least he’s trying…

1237
01:34:06,434 --> 01:34:08,959
but who knows for how long.

1238
01:34:09,039 --> 01:34:12,941
He’s lying, Mama.
He’ll never do better.

1239
01:34:13,010 --> 01:34:15,274
I know, honey.

1240
01:34:16,849 --> 01:34:20,012
Just remember what I said.
We’ll bide our time.

1241
01:34:20,121 --> 01:34:24,217
You just steer clear of him
as much as you can.

1242
01:34:24,326 --> 01:34:28,092
Doyle’s had a hard life.
It’s just about run him crazy.

1243
01:34:29,099 --> 01:34:32,466
We had hard lives too, Mama.

1244
01:34:34,941 --> 01:34:37,739
You’re a hell of a boy, Frank.

1245
01:34:39,347 --> 01:34:44,115
Someday, you’re gonna get
all the good things you deserve.

1246
01:34:44,187 --> 01:34:48,784
Karl’s gonna get some more biscuits
tonight. What do you think about that?

1247
01:34:50,028 --> 01:34:52,326
I could sure use some.

1248
01:34:59,909 --> 01:35:02,673
Karl, come unload
a generator for me.

1249
01:35:14,930 --> 01:35:17,694
Lift this thing down
and carry it to the back.

1250
01:35:17,767 --> 01:35:20,668
– It’s on the blink.
– You want us to help you lift that?

1251
01:35:20,738 --> 01:35:23,332
No. That Karl’s strong enough
to lift a bulldozer.

1252
01:35:23,408 --> 01:35:26,036
He can fix anything too.

1253
01:35:26,112 --> 01:35:29,172
He’s mentally retarded, but he’s a whiz
at small engines.

1254
01:35:30,284 --> 01:35:33,481
The Lord works in mysterious ways.

1255
01:35:33,589 --> 01:35:37,081
What I was telling you was,
he didn’t just make the team…

1256
01:35:37,194 --> 01:35:41,130
Coach says he’s gonna
start him at end on defence.

1257
01:35:41,232 --> 01:35:43,792
Guy’s a chip off the old block,
ain’t you, Steve?

1258
01:35:43,903 --> 01:35:46,997
– I guess so.
– How’s the rest of the team look?

1259
01:35:47,074 --> 01:35:49,303
Pretty good.
We expect to do well.

1260
01:35:49,377 --> 01:35:53,074
– Got a quarterback this year?
– Jeff Bailey’s boy. You know him.

1261
01:35:53,150 --> 01:35:56,142
– Got a good arm. A little slow.
– I watched him in junior high.

1262
01:35:56,220 --> 01:35:58,848
He throws the ball pretty well.
He’s taller now.

1263
01:35:58,924 --> 01:36:00,754
You gonna start at the defensive end?

1264
01:36:00,826 --> 01:36:02,816
Hup!

1265
01:36:03,897 --> 01:36:05,625
Come on, man!

1266
01:36:12,309 --> 01:36:14,538
Good job, Karl.
We got a touchdown.

1267
01:36:15,815 --> 01:36:17,748
That was a good lateral.

1268
01:36:17,817 --> 01:36:19,841
That was just like the wishbone.

1269
01:36:21,021 --> 01:36:24,821
Yes, sir.
I darned near made me a touchdown.

1270
01:36:24,893 --> 01:36:26,757
Then I seen them boys
bearing down on me.

1271
01:36:26,830 --> 01:36:30,391
Figured I better give it off
to you. I seen you following me.

1272
01:36:30,468 --> 01:36:34,234
We liable to win
if we keep this up.

1273
01:36:34,307 --> 01:36:37,401
For somebody like you,
you sure can run fast.

1274
01:36:37,477 --> 01:36:40,969
– Come on. Let’s kick off to them.
– All right, then.

1275
01:36:46,089 --> 01:36:48,649
I know you could have
scored that touchdown by yourself…

1276
01:36:48,759 --> 01:36:51,387
instead of throwing it over to me.

1277
01:36:51,464 --> 01:36:55,161
Them boys was trying to pull me down
pretty hard.

1278
01:36:55,235 --> 01:36:57,931
You’re strong.
You just threw it to me…

1279
01:36:58,005 --> 01:37:00,997
where I could score that touchdown
so I’d feel good.

1280
01:37:01,077 --> 01:37:03,944
My daddy used to do
that kind of thing.

1281
01:37:06,584 --> 01:37:09,883
It don’t matter to me about us losing.
Does it to you?

1282
01:37:09,956 --> 01:37:11,752
No, sir.

1283
01:37:11,825 --> 01:37:13,815
It was fun anyhow.

1284
01:37:13,894 --> 01:37:18,491
I wasn’t thinking about nothing else,
just like you told me I’d do.

1285
01:37:18,568 --> 01:37:20,968
Can we play every Saturday?

1286
01:37:21,071 --> 01:37:23,004
If I ain’t too stove up.

1287
01:37:23,074 --> 01:37:25,907
I ain’t like you.
I’m old and give out.

1288
01:37:29,216 --> 01:37:32,151
I’m proud of you.

1289
01:39:46,473 --> 01:39:49,806
I’d kick your head in
25 years ago.

1290
01:39:49,877 --> 01:39:53,836
You’re dead, I guess.
Where’d you go to?

1291
01:39:56,486 --> 01:39:59,455
I know, Mother. That’s kind of sad.
I was drunk when I did it.

1292
01:40:13,143 --> 01:40:15,076
I’m your boy.

1293
01:40:18,483 --> 01:40:20,416
I ain’t got no boy.

1294
01:40:23,724 --> 01:40:26,693
I’m your oldest boy,
name of Karl.

1295
01:40:26,762 --> 01:40:28,626
I ain’t got no boy.

1296
01:40:31,701 --> 01:40:34,135
They turned me loose
from the nervous hospital.

1297
01:40:34,238 --> 01:40:36,536
Said I was well.

1298
01:40:45,421 --> 01:40:50,985
I got hired on to work for Mr. Bill Cox,
fixing lawn mowers and whatnot.

1299
01:40:54,066 --> 01:40:57,729
That grass out there in the yard
growed up quite a bit.

1300
01:40:57,805 --> 01:40:59,999
I figured I might cut it for you.

1301
01:41:01,510 --> 01:41:06,539
I told you I ain’t got no boy.
Get on out of here and let me be.

1302
01:41:06,617 --> 01:41:09,450
You ain’t no kin to me.

1303
01:41:12,992 --> 01:41:15,290
I learned to read some.

1304
01:41:18,901 --> 01:41:20,993
I read the Bible quite a bit.

1305
01:41:27,379 --> 01:41:29,437
I can’t understand all of it.

1306
01:41:29,516 --> 01:41:33,077
But I reckon I understand
a good deal of it.

1307
01:41:33,153 --> 01:41:37,249
Them stories you and Mama told me,
they ain’t in there.

1308
01:41:39,463 --> 01:41:42,626
You ought not done that to your boy.

1309
01:41:44,369 --> 01:41:47,099
I studied on killing you.

1310
01:41:48,041 --> 01:41:50,099
I studied about it quite a bit.

1311
01:41:55,218 --> 01:41:57,686
But I reckon there’s no need for it
if all you’re gonna do…

1312
01:41:57,755 --> 01:42:00,849
is sit there in that chair.

1313
01:42:00,926 --> 01:42:03,918
You’ll be dead soon enough.

1314
01:42:03,996 --> 01:42:06,624
And the world’ll be shut of you.

1315
01:42:14,745 --> 01:42:17,805
You ought not kill my little brother.

1316
01:42:20,852 --> 01:42:23,320
He ought of had
a chance to growed up.

1317
01:42:25,994 --> 01:42:29,259
He would have had fun sometime.

1318
01:43:03,045 --> 01:43:04,978
Little feller.

1319
01:44:16,446 --> 01:44:21,146
What the goddamn hell
you doing up in the middle of the night?

1320
01:44:21,254 --> 01:44:23,050
What you want, hon?

1321
01:44:23,156 --> 01:44:25,123
I wanna be baptised.

1322
01:44:25,226 --> 01:44:27,694
Get baptised. then.
I don’t give a shit!

1323
01:44:27,762 --> 01:44:31,254
Call up a fucking preacher!
We can’t baptise you.

1324
01:44:31,334 --> 01:44:34,792
We’ll go see Brother Epersom tomorrow
and get you baptised.

1325
01:44:34,873 --> 01:44:38,365
It’s Sunday.
You go on back to bed now.

1326
01:44:40,147 --> 01:44:42,239
What are you doing
with that damn hammer?

1327
01:44:46,455 --> 01:44:49,856
I don’t rightly know.
I just woke up holding it.

1328
01:44:59,006 --> 01:45:01,839
– What’s he’s doing with that hammer?
– I don’t know.

1329
01:45:24,073 --> 01:45:28,373
Upon his profession of faith
in our Lord Jesus Christ…

1330
01:45:28,446 --> 01:45:31,006
in obedience under His command…

1331
01:45:31,116 --> 01:45:33,380
and by the authority of this church…

1332
01:45:33,453 --> 01:45:36,684
I indeed baptise this brother…

1333
01:45:36,758 --> 01:45:39,625
in the name of the Father
and the Son…

1334
01:45:39,695 --> 01:45:41,628
and the Holy Ghost.

1335
01:45:44,870 --> 01:45:46,632
Amen.

1336
01:45:46,705 --> 01:45:49,265
Marie, would you sing 137, please?

1337
01:45:50,644 --> 01:45:53,807
Softly and tenderly

1338
01:45:53,883 --> 01:45:56,852
Jesus is calling

1339
01:45:57,953 --> 01:46:03,358
Calling for you and for me

1340
01:46:09,103 --> 01:46:11,901
– How’d the baptising go?
– Real good.

1341
01:46:11,974 --> 01:46:13,907
Yeah? Good.

1342
01:46:14,977 --> 01:46:17,206
I’m kind of hungry.

1343
01:46:17,281 --> 01:46:19,909
Isn’t it about time to eat?

1344
01:46:19,984 --> 01:46:24,011
You know what I got a crave for?
Some of that Chicken Champ.

1345
01:46:24,090 --> 01:46:26,786
Why don’t you run down and get some?
I’ll buy.

1346
01:46:26,861 --> 01:46:28,760
Would y’all like that?

1347
01:46:28,830 --> 01:46:30,763
It sounds fine to me.

1348
01:46:30,833 --> 01:46:33,825
I’d value me a chicken leg or two.

1349
01:46:36,206 --> 01:46:40,336
– Get some of their cole slaw too.
– Okay. Y’all wanna go with me?

1350
01:46:40,413 --> 01:46:42,779
They don’t need to go with you.
There’s a ball game coming on.

1351
01:46:42,849 --> 01:46:47,081
– We’ll sit here and do man things.
– I’ll be back in a little bit.

1352
01:46:47,156 --> 01:46:50,284
– All right. Get some extra gravy.
– Okay.

1353
01:46:55,400 --> 01:46:57,925
Why don’t y’all
sit your asses down here.

1354
01:46:59,005 --> 01:47:00,938
Sit down.

1355
01:47:13,559 --> 01:47:17,586
I just wanted to get your mama
out of the house so we could talk.

1356
01:47:29,214 --> 01:47:31,147
Here’s the deal, Frank.

1357
01:47:34,121 --> 01:47:37,557
If I’m gonna throw my life away
to come live with y’all…

1358
01:47:40,063 --> 01:47:42,793
we’re gonna get some shit straight.

1359
01:47:42,900 --> 01:47:47,064
Your mama and I don’t have no problems
except for you.

1360
01:47:47,172 --> 01:47:50,573
Fact is, we never have
a bad word between us.

1361
01:47:50,643 --> 01:47:52,837
But since you do exist…

1362
01:47:52,913 --> 01:47:55,711
and I’m gonna be
the head of the household…

1363
01:47:55,784 --> 01:47:58,150
you’re gonna learn
to live by my rules.

1364
01:47:58,221 --> 01:48:02,248
The first rule is: You don’t speak
unless you’re spoken to.

1365
01:48:02,326 --> 01:48:03,952
You got me?

1366
01:48:05,030 --> 01:48:08,158
Now you stay
the hell out of my way.

1367
01:48:08,234 --> 01:48:10,896
And do what a regular kid does.

1368
01:48:11,005 --> 01:48:14,805
You’re a weird little shit, Frank.
And I don’t get you.

1369
01:48:14,877 --> 01:48:19,406
So wake up
and face what they call reality.

1370
01:48:20,351 --> 01:48:22,284
We’re gonna be a family.

1371
01:48:22,353 --> 01:48:24,787
My family.

1372
01:48:24,857 --> 01:48:27,519
I’ll be paying all the bills.

1373
01:48:27,595 --> 01:48:30,325
So that means,
you’re stuck with my ass…

1374
01:48:30,399 --> 01:48:32,332
but I ain’t your daddy.

1375
01:48:33,403 --> 01:48:35,928
You just act like I am.

1376
01:48:36,006 --> 01:48:37,973
The other thing I say is…

1377
01:48:38,043 --> 01:48:40,010
your buddy Karl is going.

1378
01:48:41,681 --> 01:48:44,241
We can’t be no normal family
with him living in the garage…

1379
01:48:44,318 --> 01:48:47,412
and coming in the bedroom
at 4:00 in the morning with hammers.

1380
01:48:47,489 --> 01:48:49,957
Karl could stay if he wants to.
Mama said –

1381
01:48:50,025 --> 01:48:51,958
What I tell you about your mama?

1382
01:48:52,028 --> 01:48:55,429
Mister, don’t you never
lay another hand on that boy.

1383
01:48:55,501 --> 01:48:58,527
– You understand me?
– Let go of my hand, you retard.

1384
01:48:58,604 --> 01:49:02,040
Get out there!
Get your shit and get out!

1385
01:49:04,212 --> 01:49:07,204
That’s a wake-up call, Frankie.

1386
01:49:07,283 --> 01:49:09,409
You remember what I said
about reality!

1387
01:49:10,488 --> 01:49:12,421
Get out, retard.

1388
01:49:38,293 --> 01:49:42,059
Where you going?
Didn’t you want some chicken and things?

1389
01:49:42,132 --> 01:49:45,397
No, ma’am.
I’m going off somewheres.

1390
01:49:45,469 --> 01:49:48,165
Well, okay.
I got you some.

1391
01:49:48,273 --> 01:49:50,502
Frank – he went off somewheres too.

1392
01:49:50,577 --> 01:49:53,011
So when you go in there,
he won’t be indoors.

1393
01:49:53,079 --> 01:49:55,069
Where did he go?
What’s going on?

1394
01:49:55,149 --> 01:49:57,879
He just wanted to go play, I reckon.

1395
01:49:57,987 --> 01:49:59,954
You go in and eat
with that Doyle…

1396
01:50:00,022 --> 01:50:02,582
and don’t worry yourself none.

1397
01:50:02,694 --> 01:50:04,661
All right, then.

1398
01:50:04,730 --> 01:50:06,663
Well, I’ll see you later.

1399
01:50:06,732 --> 01:50:08,756
If you see Frank,
tell him to come home.

1400
01:50:08,835 --> 01:50:10,995
I don’t get to see him
except Sundays.

1401
01:50:11,071 --> 01:50:13,767
He can go play tomorrow.

1402
01:50:13,842 --> 01:50:15,775
– Ma’am?
– Yeah?

1403
01:50:19,850 --> 01:50:22,910
You’re a good mama to that boy.

1404
01:50:23,022 --> 01:50:25,114
You care for him.

1405
01:50:25,225 --> 01:50:28,126
You work hard to care for him.

1406
01:50:28,195 --> 01:50:30,755
You light him up in his eyes.

1407
01:50:30,865 --> 01:50:32,798
I’ve seen it.

1408
01:50:34,003 --> 01:50:37,666
That boy wouldn’t know what to do
without you.

1409
01:50:37,742 --> 01:50:40,233
Thank you.
That’s real good of you to say.

1410
01:50:40,312 --> 01:50:43,008
I wouldn’t know what to do
without him either.

1411
01:50:43,083 --> 01:50:45,677
You been real good to me too.

1412
01:50:45,754 --> 01:50:50,088
It ain’t everybody that’d make biscuits
in the middle of the night.

1413
01:50:50,159 --> 01:50:53,094
You and that boy’s
given me a good feeling.

1414
01:50:54,164 --> 01:50:56,826
We sure like having you.

1415
01:50:56,902 --> 01:50:58,835
Thank you.

1416
01:51:00,607 --> 01:51:03,633
I’m just now getting around
to telling you –

1417
01:51:03,745 --> 01:51:08,205
But I fixed that washing machine so that
boy ain’t gotta tote laundry no more.

1418
01:51:08,318 --> 01:51:10,444
Thank you.

1419
01:51:16,228 --> 01:51:18,161
You been real good to me.

1420
01:51:35,422 --> 01:51:38,323
Hey, Karl.
How’d you know I’d come out here?

1421
01:51:38,393 --> 01:51:41,885
I knowed you’d be out here.

1422
01:51:41,997 --> 01:51:44,557
What you doing
digging with that stub?

1423
01:51:44,668 --> 01:51:47,796
Just digging.
I ain’t never gonna be happy now.

1424
01:51:47,905 --> 01:51:51,397
Not with that son-of-a-bitch
moving in for good.

1425
01:51:51,478 --> 01:51:54,379
I wish me and you and Mama
would just run away.

1426
01:51:54,448 --> 01:51:56,712
She said…

1427
01:51:56,785 --> 01:51:59,219
wherever we went,
he’d find us.

1428
01:51:59,287 --> 01:52:04,487
He’s crazy. Sometimes I think it’d been
better off if I wasn’t even born.

1429
01:52:05,563 --> 01:52:08,031
I’m glad of it
you was borned.

1430
01:52:11,037 --> 01:52:14,768
I don’t reckon I’m gonna be out there
in the garage no more.

1431
01:52:14,843 --> 01:52:17,607
You have to.
You have to look out for me.

1432
01:52:17,713 --> 01:52:20,443
You can’t let that
son-of-a-bitch run you off.

1433
01:52:20,551 --> 01:52:24,920
You just a boy.
You ought not use language like that.

1434
01:52:26,092 --> 01:52:28,561
I don’t mean to say nothing
bad about you…

1435
01:52:28,562 --> 01:52:32,396
but why don’t you stop Doyle
when he’s being that way?

1436
01:52:33,536 --> 01:52:36,061
You’re older than him.
You’re strong too.

1437
01:52:37,507 --> 01:52:41,500
My daddy wouldn’t let him
do that to me and Mama.

1438
01:52:43,349 --> 01:52:46,318
That feller’s a whole site
meaner than me.

1439
01:52:46,420 --> 01:52:48,752
He’d just whup the tar out of me.

1440
01:52:48,824 --> 01:52:51,384
Yeah. I guess so.

1441
01:52:53,062 --> 01:52:55,222
I’m real tired,
you know that?

1442
01:52:56,668 --> 01:52:59,501
A boy my age shouldn’t
be tired of things.

1443
01:53:02,976 --> 01:53:04,909
I’m tired too.

1444
01:53:07,917 --> 01:53:12,081
Just ’cause I ain’t gonna be
around no more, maybe…

1445
01:53:12,155 --> 01:53:14,623
that don’t mean
I don’t care for you.

1446
01:53:14,693 --> 01:53:16,991
I care for you a good deal.

1447
01:53:17,063 --> 01:53:20,123
I care for you more
than anything else there is.

1448
01:53:20,200 --> 01:53:22,668
You and me made friends
right off the bat.

1449
01:53:23,772 --> 01:53:26,297
I care for you too.
But you’ll be around.

1450
01:53:26,409 --> 01:53:28,741
Don’t say that.

1451
01:53:28,813 --> 01:53:32,078
It don’t make no difference
where I was to be.

1452
01:53:32,149 --> 01:53:36,951
We’ll always be friends.
Can’t nobody stop that.

1453
01:53:46,871 --> 01:53:50,170
I aim for you to have these books.

1454
01:53:50,241 --> 01:53:53,142
You don’t wanna give away
all your books.

1455
01:53:53,246 --> 01:53:55,270
I aim for you to have them.

1456
01:54:04,094 --> 01:54:08,121
Maybe you can make more sense of them
than I can.

1457
01:54:08,199 --> 01:54:13,365
I made you a bookmarker and put it
in that book on Christmas.

1458
01:54:17,279 --> 01:54:19,212
Thanks.

1459
01:54:21,018 --> 01:54:24,647
You know when you got a feeling
and you don’t know why?

1460
01:54:24,723 --> 01:54:27,248
Yes, sir.

1461
01:54:27,327 --> 01:54:30,785
I got a feeling today.

1462
01:54:30,898 --> 01:54:33,731
Reckon, what kind of a feeling?

1463
01:54:33,836 --> 01:54:37,328
Like something different.
I don’t know.

1464
01:54:40,078 --> 01:54:42,045
You leaving, ain’t you?

1465
01:54:52,128 --> 01:54:55,495
Would you do something for me
if I was to ask you to?

1466
01:54:55,566 --> 01:54:59,093
You know I would.
Whatever you want.

1467
01:55:01,374 --> 01:55:03,534
When you leave outta here tonight…

1468
01:55:03,644 --> 01:55:07,546
I don’t want you going over there
and staying with that Doyle.

1469
01:55:10,020 --> 01:55:14,856
He’s got it out for you tonight.
I got me a feeling too.

1470
01:55:14,926 --> 01:55:18,760
You ought not be over there
when he’s all liquored up and mean.

1471
01:55:18,831 --> 01:55:20,764
Your mama neither.

1472
01:55:21,835 --> 01:55:26,238
When you get up here and leave, I want
you to go to that feller’s house –

1473
01:55:26,308 --> 01:55:28,708
your mama’s friend.

1474
01:55:31,282 --> 01:55:34,479
I want you to give me your word on it.

1475
01:55:34,553 --> 01:55:37,454
Okay. I give you my word on it.

1476
01:55:39,059 --> 01:55:42,859
Is everything gonna be okay?
Are you all right?

1477
01:55:47,004 --> 01:55:50,735
Yeah, everything’s gonna be all right,
boy.

1478
01:55:58,252 --> 01:56:00,846
I kind of wanna put my arm
around you for a minute…

1479
01:56:00,923 --> 01:56:04,359
then I’m gonna get up
and leave out of here.

1480
01:56:32,333 --> 01:56:35,200
I love you, boy.

1481
01:56:36,773 --> 01:56:38,763
I love you too.

1482
01:56:42,615 --> 01:56:45,277
All right, then.

1483
01:57:25,339 --> 01:57:27,739
What are you doing here?
You wanna come in?

1484
01:57:27,810 --> 01:57:32,339
I ain’t staying.
I need to ask you for a favour.

1485
01:57:34,420 --> 01:57:37,753
This evening
I want you to go get Miss Wheatley…

1486
01:57:37,824 --> 01:57:41,954
and let her and Frank
stay over here with you tonight.

1487
01:57:42,030 --> 01:57:44,590
What’s wrong?
Is everything all right?

1488
01:57:44,666 --> 01:57:46,860
That Doyle…

1489
01:57:46,936 --> 01:57:51,704
he’s in a bad way again with
that drinking and being mean to folks.

1490
01:57:51,810 --> 01:57:54,210
I want you to give me your word
you’ll do it.

1491
01:57:54,313 --> 01:57:57,282
Sure. Okay.
He hasn’t hurt them, has he?

1492
01:57:57,352 --> 01:57:59,718
No, sir.
Not yet.

1493
01:58:00,788 --> 01:58:02,482
Here.

1494
01:58:02,558 --> 01:58:04,958
I want you to give that
to Miss Wheatley.

1495
01:58:05,028 --> 01:58:06,961
It ain’t much…

1496
01:58:07,031 --> 01:58:10,330
but they might be
a little something there to help out.

1497
01:58:10,402 --> 01:58:14,338
It’s what I made fixing lawn mowers
and whatnot for Bill Cox.

1498
01:58:15,944 --> 01:58:18,811
How about you, Karl?
You wanna stay here?

1499
01:58:20,216 --> 01:58:25,655
I don’t reckon that you have to go with
women to be a good daddy to a boy.

1500
01:58:25,690 --> 01:58:28,921
You been real square
dealing with me.

1501
01:58:28,995 --> 01:58:32,761
Bible says two men
ought not lay together.

1502
01:58:34,469 --> 01:58:40,102
But I bet you the good Lord
wouldn’t send nobody like you to Hades.

1503
01:58:41,512 --> 01:58:45,004
That boy – Frank –

1504
01:58:45,084 --> 01:58:48,349
he lives inside of his own heart.

1505
01:58:48,422 --> 01:58:51,289
That’s an awful big place to live in.

1506
01:58:53,228 --> 01:58:55,856
You take care of that boy.

1507
01:58:59,437 --> 01:59:02,133
I will.

1508
02:01:56,081 --> 02:01:58,048
Where’s everybody else?

1509
02:02:05,729 --> 02:02:07,662
You seen them?

1510
02:02:15,008 --> 02:02:18,535
Didn’t I tell you
to get moved out of here?

1511
02:02:21,985 --> 02:02:25,512
How does a feller go about
getting hold of the police?

1512
02:02:31,732 --> 02:02:34,496
Use the fucking phone, I guess.

1513
02:02:35,837 --> 02:02:38,101
Which numbers do you put in?

1514
02:02:46,352 --> 02:02:49,287
Can’t you see I’m trying to relax?

1515
02:02:51,558 --> 02:02:55,460
I thought I told you
to get out of here and leave me alone.

1516
02:03:00,638 --> 02:03:03,163
What the hell you doing
with that lawn mower blade?

1517
02:03:04,109 --> 02:03:06,577
I aim to kill you with it.

1518
02:03:20,131 --> 02:03:23,157
To call the police you push…

1519
02:03:23,236 --> 02:03:27,673
nine, one, one.

1520
02:03:32,916 --> 02:03:35,646
Just tell them
to bring an ambulance.

1521
02:03:38,725 --> 02:03:42,024
Or a “hearst,”
if you’re gonna kill me.

1522
02:04:41,678 --> 02:04:43,942
Yes, ma’am.

1523
02:04:44,015 --> 02:04:46,984
I need the police
sent over here to the Wheatley house.

1524
02:04:50,123 --> 02:04:55,357
I’ve killed Doyle Hargraves
with a lawn mower blade.

1525
02:04:55,431 --> 02:04:59,595
Yes, ma’am.
I’m right sure of it.

1526
02:04:59,670 --> 02:05:02,332
I hit him
two good whacks with it.

1527
02:05:02,407 --> 02:05:06,741
That second one
just plumb near cut his head in two.

1528
02:05:10,051 --> 02:05:12,315
It’s a little old white house…

1529
02:05:12,387 --> 02:05:17,052
on the corner of Vine Street
and some other street.

1530
02:05:17,126 --> 02:05:22,429
There’s a truck out front, says
“Doyle Hargraves Construction” on it.

1531
02:05:25,105 --> 02:05:27,938
I’ll be sitting here
waiting on you.

1532
02:05:29,044 --> 02:05:32,707
And Doyle said
besides sending the police…

1533
02:05:32,782 --> 02:05:35,046
you might wanna send an ambulance…

1534
02:05:35,118 --> 02:05:37,484
or a “hearst.”

1535
02:05:39,091 --> 02:05:40,990
Thank you.

1536
02:06:44,716 --> 02:06:46,182
So…

1537
02:06:47,218 --> 02:06:51,120
now on the third day…

1538
02:06:51,191 --> 02:06:56,323
I washed her,
’cause she wasn’t too clean, you know.

1539
02:06:56,398 --> 02:06:59,196
But I got all the right spots.

1540
02:06:59,268 --> 02:07:01,201
She was the first one I ever kept…

1541
02:07:01,271 --> 02:07:06,300
’cause I get bored real easy –
I got a short attention span, you know.

1542
02:07:07,880 --> 02:07:13,410
Now I can’t say
that she enjoyed her stay…

1543
02:07:15,959 --> 02:07:20,522
with that washcloth I put in her mouth
and held in place with duct tape.

1544
02:07:20,632 --> 02:07:22,599
Kept her complaining down to a minimum.

1545
02:07:22,668 --> 02:07:24,932
I don’t like people
who talk all the time.

1546
02:07:25,004 --> 02:07:27,472
I like to do all the talking.

1547
02:07:27,541 --> 02:07:30,567
That’s why I think I’m
so fond of you…

1548
02:07:30,645 --> 02:07:33,580
’cause you just so easygoing, you know.

1549
02:07:36,487 --> 02:07:41,050
Although, I do sense a little tension
in you from time to time.

1550
02:07:43,997 --> 02:07:46,966
So you were out in the world?

1551
02:07:48,537 --> 02:07:51,438
Did you have fun?
Did you make any acquaintances?

1552
02:07:52,509 --> 02:07:56,104
There was a boy.
We made friends.

1553
02:07:56,215 --> 02:07:58,148
I’ll bet you did.

1554
02:08:01,655 --> 02:08:06,252
I was never bent that way.
I was bent the other way.

1555
02:08:07,330 --> 02:08:09,126
So?

1556
02:08:10,701 --> 02:08:15,401
What was it like out there
in the world?

1557
02:08:16,676 --> 02:08:18,609
It was too big.

1558
02:08:21,816 --> 02:08:24,182
It’s not too big in here, is it?

1559
02:08:32,232 --> 02:08:35,065
You know something?

1560
02:08:35,135 --> 02:08:37,068
I feel real…

1561
02:08:38,172 --> 02:08:40,800
generous today –
I feel like listening.

1562
02:08:42,111 --> 02:08:44,579
I bet you got plenty to tell.

1563
02:08:50,457 --> 02:08:52,925
Who’d you kill?

1564
02:08:53,994 --> 02:08:56,292
Was it the boy?

1565
02:08:56,364 --> 02:08:59,561
Don’t you say nothing
about that boy.

1566
02:09:05,912 --> 02:09:10,372
Fact of business,
don’t you say another word to me.

1567
02:09:10,484 --> 02:09:13,715
I ain’t listening to you no more.

1568
02:09:28,475 --> 02:09:30,066
Yeah.
